segments.text: So, we were talking about General Wainwright.
Well, General Wainwright and I were together on several trips.
He seemed to take a liking to me.
It might have been partly due to the fact that he knew my cousin, Fletcher Sharp, so well.
But anyway, he and I, we went out to, I think to Bandera or someplace and they gave him a beautiful horse and a silver mounted saddle and
made him an honorary deputy sheriff of Bandera County, and made me an honorary deputy sheriff of Bandera County.
On another trip, I was with about 18 other general officers and wives who were guests of the Mexican government, and on that trip,

We would go- I've been to Mexico City so many times that it was uninteresting to me and it was uninteresting to General Wainwright after so long time because he was looking for a place to get a drink.
So about 11 a.m. with all the sights anyway about 11 a.m. General Wainwright would say, come on Beverly let's go strike a blow for liberty.
We'd repair the nearest bar for a drink and let the rest of the party go.
Well, that got to be sort of routine.
Well, I liked the old fellow, but he was pretty well shot physically when he got home.
What a shame.
He needed whiskey just to keep going.
How about General Spouts?
General who?
Spouts.
Spots.
S-P-A-A-T-Z.
Spatz.
Who?
Spatz.
S-P-A-A-T-Z.
Oh, Spatz.
That's pronounced Spatz.
Oh, he was a fine officer.
He was our first Chief of Air Force.
After we got the separate Air Force, he was the first man to be selected Chief of Air Force.
I was on two trips with him.
One to
Rio and Sao Paulo, Brazil and on another trip to Mexico City and on down to Acapulco on a fishing trip.
And he and I were good friends.
Now why did you, was this after the war?
Yeah.
Why did you go to Mexico after the war so often?
Was this to build relations?
Oh, we had fine relations with the Mexican Air Force and the Mexican General Salinas.
He was chief of the Mexican Air Force.
He used to come up and visit me and Kelly quite often.
Sometimes he'd bring his wife along and do a little shopping at our post exchange.
You all sound like a scandal sheet in here.
Well, honey, this doesn't go any farther than that.
I hope not.
We're just talking about famous people.
Yeah, Spots and I were good friends.
We played gin and rummy all the way from Washington to Rio and Sao Paulo and all the way back to Washington.
Kept books on it and broke exactly even.
Really?
Now while you were the commander at Kelly, in 1946 you received an honorary doctorate of law from Texas A&M.
Yeah.
Tell me about that.
Well, at that time there were about 28 or 29 general officers, A&M men.
I think maybe it was one admiral and 28 generals.
And they decided to make us all honorary doctors of law.
And they also invited Eisenhower to come at the same time and made him an honorary doctor of law.
So that's the only degree I have.
I never finished the A&M.
I went there just for two years.
What did you think of the ceremony?
It was very nice.
I now made an acceptance speech for all of it.
It's just one of those nice things that happen to you if you're in a high place.
General officers, you get a lot of medals and you get these honorary degrees.
What was the highest ranking A&M officer at the time?
Do you remember?
Was he a horse?
No, I think it was three-star.
I think it was Lieutenant General Bruce.
Somewhere I've got a list of the officers that received that.
Well, I'm sure we do it in the archives too, and I'm sure they have that in the battalion.
I remember there was a General Moore, and he wasn't there because I think he was in the hospital.
He had been over in Corregidor.
In May of 1947, you lost your command and you were transferred.
What were your feelings about that?
In 1947, I... Did I say 74?
I meant 47.
Yep, 47.
I was ordered to Brazil, is that what you're talking about?
Yeah, I was wondering about your feelings.
Well, I knew I couldn't be commanding general at Kelly forever, so I'd already held the job longer than anybody previous to me.
So, of course, I figured, well, that's what Washington wants, that's what I want, so I went down there.
I didn't have anything to do when I got there much,
As the military and the Air Attach in Debrazile.
Combination.
Army Attach, as the military Attach and Air Attach combination.
That's when we were still part of the Army.
While I was down there, the separate Air Force Act went through and then I just became the Air Attach.
I got along fine with Brazil and made some fine friends down there.
I made some friends among other Attachs, a Canadian Attach, a Spanish-era Attach, and his wife were good friends of ours.
Did you travel throughout the country quite a bit?
Yes, I traveled.
I had a DC-3 assigned to me for the purpose of
getting around and inspecting other countries, and I certainly took advantage of that by going to every country in South America.
Really?
Including the Dutch, the Guyana, the Dutch Guyana, the British Guyana, and British Guyana.
And sometimes I'd take other attachs and their wives along, and take my wife along, and just sightseeing business.
It's a goodwill.
Good relations.
Goodwill, and that's about all we got.
And how were the relations with South America?
All good.
Good?
All good, yeah.
Of course, at this time, we were fighting communism in Europe, at least ideologically, and also in Latin America.
Was there fear that communists might win some victories in South America?
At that time, communism hadn't crept in anywhere in South America, not even Georgetown, British Ghana.
I did make one interesting trip.
Got some Brazilian officers.

and we took off and flew over to Bolivia in a place called Santa Clara de la Sierra, and then I flew directly north to try to hit a town called Porto Velho, which is at the end of a railroad, a railroad about
150 mile long railroad that goes from Puerto Velho south into where they used to get rubber.
It was made, the railroad was put in there just to ship the raw rubber down to Puerto Velho where it was processed into big balls about this big around.
And then it was shipped by steamer from Puerto Velho down through Manaus and on north up the Amazon River.
at the United States and wherever else in Hawaii.
I saw a lot of jungle on that trip.
If the airplane had gone down, we'd have been like the Kingsley I expected in Nicaragua.
They probably never found us.
In Puerto Vallejo, they treated us right royally.
I even made a speech in Portuguese after a couple of drinks.
I'd loosen up my tongue.
They took us out the next day to an Indian camp along the river there.
We bought some bows and arrows and beads and necklaces and whatnot.
And the next day we flew on down to Manalas and we were guests of the governor of the territory of Manalas, the territory of Amazonas.
and he took us out on his yacht and had lunch.
Anybody who wanted to fish could fish.
I didn't want to fish, so I never did care much about fishing.
The confluence of the three rivers that come together there in Manaus, one from the west that rides in Peru and Venezuela,
One from the south, which Puerto Vallarta is on, that's called the Madera River.
And one from the southeast, I forget the name of that river, but they all come together there at Manaus to form the Amazon.
And that Amazon River at Manaus is 50 feet deep.
Steamers, ocean-going steamers, can come all the way up there.
from a thousand miles down at the port.
That's the land.
Come up there.
That was a river a thousand miles to Manalas.
It is so level that the tide rises and falls there.
No kidding.
At Manalas.
Well, it sounds like
Compared to the responsibilities of having Kelly Air Force Base, this is pretty easy duty.
Yeah, it was too easy for me.
I like work I can get my teeth into.
And this is more of being a diplomat, wasn't it, than being an officer?
Yeah, just friendly diplomatic stuff.
The Brazilian were very friendly with us.
I had a whole division over in Italy fighting with us.
And like a squadron of air force over there.
And Marshal Mascarenhas, who was commanding over in Italy, he wrote a book and gave me an autographed copy of it here.
Yeah, you can read that someday when you want.
How nice.
I could read it if I wanted to, but I don't.
expeditionary force that they have been.
Were you happy to leave the job?
I was happy to leave Brazil and get back to this country.
Why?
Because living conditions in Rio are poor.
It's very, very expensive.
I had to pay to rent an apartment.
I had to pay
under the table money, a thousand cruzeros, which at that time was about $250, just for the privilege of signing a lease on, at the lawful rate, had rent control.
And that went against my grain, of course, and it was a very poor, it was a brand new
apartment building, but they were poorly constructed.
No heat in it at all, and it gets cold there in the wintertime.
We got a little electric heater, and that soon burned out the wiring, and we put a cheap wiring in the thing.
Our windows fit so poorly that we took towels and stuff.
They were double-hung windows, and we took towels and stuff.
I was wondering why they had a brigadier general as the attache.
Isn't it usually a colonel?
No, that's what they had.
Some had one in Argentina and one in Brazil.
I believe Venezuela had a brigadier general, I'm not sure.
Apparently they bumped up the rank that they deserved.
So when you came back to the United States in 1948, then what?
Did you know that you were going to retire then?
I figured, yeah.
You figured that you would?
I figured I was going to retire, and they put me on them.
promotion board first in Washington on temporary duty there, and when I got through that duty, I asked to be sent back to Kelly Field and put on a retired list, which I did.
Well, it says you were ordered into retirement.
Yeah.
Well, how did that come about?
Well, that's the way that, that's the way it's worded.
You're ordered into retirement.
But you had decided
I decided I wanted to retire, yeah.
When did you decide that?
Down in Brazil when I got this hip arthritis in my head.
So, I retired in July 31st, I believe it was, 1949.
How'd you feel on your retirement day?
Oh, I felt like I was too young to just quit work.
I was 52 years old, so I started looking around.
I tried to start a bank there at Kellyfield, and I had all those civilian employees, and not all of them, a great many of them wanted to put money in it.
I wrote to all the general officers I knew that they all wanted stock in the bank, but I hadn't done my homework, so I didn't know how to start a bank.
I wanted to be president of the bank.
Kelly, that's what I wanted to do.
I hadn't done my homework, so I never could get it started.
I've got one there now.
Did you look forward to civilian life?
Oh, yeah.
Did they put a big, did they have a nice celebration for you?
Well, they had a parade, yeah.
Was that at Kelly?
At Kelly, yeah.
Now, when you were advancing in your military career, at first, of course, it was a very slow advancement because of the promotion system, and then it was very quick advancement.
But did you leave your advancement to fate, or did you, were you consciously, did you think that you had some control over your promotions?
No, I didn't have any control over them.
I could have probably gotten a second and a third star if I wanted to more or less be conformist to what everybody wanted, I mean the higher ups.
I was too much of an individualist to be promoted.
I won my promotion in spite of the fact that
If I was a maverick, that's the best way I could get.
Well, can you give me some examples of you being a maverick?
Oh, yes, I never...
If I thought my commanding officer was wrong, I would hesitate to go in and tell him things like that.
If I thought the policy was wrong, I'd write a letter about it or talk about it.
Was there some specific policy or letter that you wrote that really got you in trouble?
No.
Oh, yeah.
I got in touch with General Sandy Fairchild in Washington when I was there as chief of the inspection.
He wanted me to be new, and I knew all these basic matters.
He wanted me to give him a secret report on that and the poor ones.
And I told him that I didn't like to give secret reports on anybody.
If I gave a report on a substance, such an officer was a poor base commander, I would put it in a letter and cite the reasons and send it to the base, said base commander, for comment.
And Sandy didn't like that.
He wanted a secret business.
So he never did like me after that.
And he was a very powerful marshal.
He was Vandenberg's assistant when Vandenberg was chief of staff.
Vandenberg was a good friend of mine.
But Fairchild was
down on me.
And that was one reason I never got any higher, which it didn't bother me.
I wasn't out to push myself up.
Would you consider yourself ambitious?
Not very many people make general.
I don't think that
I was ambitious.
I wanted whatever I was due, justly due.
You wanted to do the job, right?
I don't think that I was ever trying to push myself for a promotion.
I can't remember.
But do you think that as far as advancement is concerned, I'm interested in the question of people advance
to become leaders in the military the same way?
Do you do the same things as you advance to become leaders in the corporate world or the professional world?
I expect it's going to be the same.
I don't know.
I never thought of it.
I never thought of it that way.
But I expect it.
There's a lot of favoritism, I expect it, in the corporate world and promotion.
And I know there is.
military.
Well, what do you mean a lot of favoritism?
Do you think there's more favoritism in the military or do you think it's...
There's some favoritism.
You can't get away from it.
Joe Doakes is the head of mine in Washington.
He has his friends that he's known since they went through the academy together.
They went through A&M together.
They were buddies in the air tactical school.
You can't get away from favoritism and promotions.
These big heads of corporations, they're bound to have their own favorites.
Do you think that there's sort of a West Point club in which the people, you know, there's always this grumbling that people at West Point get promoted fast?
I don't think they do in the Air Force.
You can look over there.
The generals in the Air Force, I think you'll find just as many from one school as another almost.
And maybe we have more from West Point, yes, and say Georgia Tech, maybe more than the A&M.
But that's their business.
They turn out, what, 1,400 a year or 1,200 or something like that.
And career men and...
I think there's bound to be more general officers from West Point than there is from these other schools.
So I wouldn't call that favorite to me.
Okay.
Now, you wrote that memorandum on leadership, and we're going to keep that on file there, and we're going to send it back here.
But I'd like you to define leadership for me, if you would.
Well, let me see my notes here.
It's hard, it's hard to define it.
The first question I think was probably why certain people get to be leaders.
They have the ability inherently enhanced by
living in freedom, and so on and so forth.
I got all these answers here.
And I think you can gather from that what my general philosophy is on leadership.
We'll keep that there.
Go ahead.
Well, Xerox, in the military, there's different types of leaders, of course.
One was sort of the combat-type Patton, and another one was sort of the manager-type Eisenhower.
Yeah.
What type do you think you were?
I think I was a management type.
Okay.
I never was in combat.
I practiced for it when I was a pursuit commander.
Okay.
Now finally, I'd just like to ask you a couple of questions about Texas A&M and your ideas on Texas A&M.
I hate to see the Corps, such a small percentage of the men who go there, and I guess women too.
Women look like women are going to get into the armed forces, and what do we got, about 15% women now?
What's your opinion of that?
I think it's possibly 15% of the jobs that can be done by women, but I think it'd be better if we didn't have them.
I think it'd be better if we had just men.
Okay.
What do you think about women being at Texas A&M?
When you went to A&M, there weren't any women.
Well... Any women students.
What do you think about allowing them in Texas A&M?
Well, since Texas A&M is not primarily a military school, I guess I see no reason why they shouldn't be there.
It's a primary and educational institution, and there's a certain percentage of women that should be right along with the men when it comes to education.
Okay.
Now, during the 1960s, we allowed General Rutter.
Did you ever know General Rutter, by the way?
No, I didn't.
When General Rudder was the president and he allowed women in.
Also, during the 1960s, blacks were allowed into Texas A&M for the first time.
What was your opinion of that?
Wax?
Blacks.
Oh, blacks.
Well, I think they deserve to be in there, the same as whites, if they can keep up.
Okay.
I think there's a certain percentage of blacks that have just as fine brains as...
Above average whites.
The percentage is lower than whites for many, many reasons.
But there's some blacks that have become, I think, brilliant men and brilliant leaders.
You didn't have any blacks in the Air Force in integrated units until after you retired.
I believe not, yeah.
I think they were just coming in.
And what was your opinion toward integrating the Air Force?
It was okay with me.
I don't think you can discriminate against, or should discriminate against blacks due to color.
Okay.
And finally, what do you think about now, as you say, the Corps is a small percentage of students at A&M because it's no longer mandatory for people to be in the Corps of Cadets at Texas A&M.
What's your opinion of ending the mandatory rule?
Well, as I said before, it's not primarily a military institution.
Right.
I see no reason why it should be mandatory for them to be in the Corps.
I'd like to see more of them volunteer to be in the Corps, but that may come later.
We had a long period here of permissiveness where we were raising a bunch of brats.
I'm sure some of them got into A&M and we wouldn't even want them in the Corps.
I look to see more, I expect to see more of the students that are in the Corps in the future than they are now.
I hope so.
What do you think about reinstating the draft?
Do you think we should have a volunteer service or a draft?
I don't think women should be drafted.
Well, what about men?
Right now we have a volunteer service.
I think it was a mistake to ever put it in.
And I think we'll eventually have to probably go back to the draft just to keep up our strength in our forces.
If you keep trying to pay them as much as they were getting civilian lives, it looks to me like it makes the top heavy in pay.
versus equipment, hardware and software.
Yeah, I think Nixon made a mistake in demanding him the draft because it's going to be awful hard to put it back in.
Yeah, sure it is.
I'm about out of questions, General.
Is there anything else that you'd like to talk about as far as your career?
We have your manuscript that I'm going to take back, which is your memoirs, and your ideas of leadership, which are down on paper in El Xerox.
Is there anything that you think we should talk about?
I can't think of anything, Terry.
I think we've covered everything that I can think of, and if there's anything that I think of,
later why I can put it in under remarks.
Sure, you can edit it right in.
And I may think of some other things, but right now I'm out of ideas.
Thank you very much in general for this interview.
Well, I'm very happy to do it.
